# Talos secrets + machine-generated credentials — NEVER commit unencrypted (public repo).
# These hold LIVE secrets: Tailscale auth key, cluster CA private keys, admin key.
# Keep them ONLY on the operator's workstation (talenv/talsecret) — they're inputs
# talhelper reads at genconfig time. The generated machine configs + talosconfig +
# kubeconfig are derived credentials and equally secret.
talenv.yaml
talsecret.yaml
kubeconfig

# age PRIVATE key — the new linchpin secret (decrypts talsecret/talenv). Gitignored +
# stored in the handoff vault. (Default sops location is ~/.config/sops/age/keys.txt,
# outside the repo; this guards against a stray copy landing in the cluster dir.)
*.agekey
age-key.txt
keys.txt

# talsecret.sops.yaml / talenv.sops.yaml stay IGNORED until PROVEN sops-encrypted.
# Once the .sops.yaml recipient is filled + `sops -e -i` has run — verify the file has
# ENC[…] values + a `sops:` stanza AND `grep -iE 'BEGIN .*PRIVATE KEY|tskey-auth-'`
# finds NOTHING — the ENCRYPTED file MAY be committed with `git add -f`. Keeping them
# ignored by DEFAULT is the safety net: an un-encrypted talsecret/talenv can never be
# committed by accident — that was the B2 leak.
talsecret.sops.yaml
talenv.sops.yaml

# NOTE: the rendered talhelper output (clusterconfig/capstone-*.yaml + talosconfig)
# is already ignored by clusters/real-talos/clusterconfig/.gitignore — those carry
# the same CA material and must also stay out of git.
